1
00:00:07,263 --> 00:00:08,841
I saw someone drowning me.

2
00:00:09,009 --> 00:00:11,938
How do I atone for something?
I haven't done yet.

3
00:00:12,184 --> 00:00:15,392
The man you might be sleeping with in
six months' time was in our living room,

4
00:00:15,517 --> 00:00:18,017
and I sure as hell didn't bring him
into our lives. You did!

5
00:00:18,186 --> 00:00:20,063
All the old patterns are back, Mark.

6
00:00:20,367 --> 00:00:23,525
It's about trust,
and we don't trust each other anymore.

7
00:00:23,817 --> 00:00:26,859
I had a vision of Fiona Banks.
Let's see if she had a vision of me.

8
00:00:27,027 --> 00:00:30,198
I know why you're calling.
<i>It's to do with the Rutherford case.</i>

9
00:00:30,323 --> 00:00:33,484
You've been acting weird
for a couple of weeks yourself.

10
00:00:33,867 --> 00:00:36,401
"Blue Hand"...
It's a clue from Mark's board.

11
00:00:48,908 --> 00:00:49,958
<i>Dear Celia,</i>

12
00:00:51,064 --> 00:00:54,273
<i>I don't know your last name,
and I don't know where you live,</i>

13
00:00:56,449 --> 00:00:58,529
<i>but I know you have two young boys,</i>

14
00:00:58,722 --> 00:01:00,023
<i>twins, I believe.</i>

15
00:01:02,487 --> 00:01:04,914
<i>And I know you didn't have
a flash-forward.</i>

16
00:01:06,257 --> 00:01:08,672
<i>I understand how terrifying that is</i>

17
00:01:08,999 --> 00:01:10,945
<i>and how powerless
you must be feeling.</i>

18
00:01:11,659 --> 00:01:13,780
<i>But I want you to know
that you are not alone.</i>

19
00:01:32,541 --> 00:01:34,235
E-mailing your other girlfriend?

20
00:01:34,730 --> 00:01:36,291
No, we broke up.

21
00:01:36,609 --> 00:01:37,932
This is just porn.

22
00:01:39,474 --> 00:01:42,472
I'm in pre-trial conference all day,
so unreachable, but don't forget,

23
00:01:42,597 --> 00:01:44,922
- we need to sign off on the proofs.
- Proofs?

24
00:01:45,047 --> 00:01:46,848
- For the wedding invitations.
- Right.

25
00:01:46,973 --> 00:01:49,031
Bet you 20 bucks
they spell my name wrong.

26
00:01:49,156 --> 00:01:50,833
Bet you $100 they got mine wrong.

27
00:01:50,958 --> 00:01:53,583
They say couples
with commonly misspelled names

28
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:55,555
are the most successful.

29
00:01:56,030 --> 00:01:57,030
Really?

30
00:02:00,145 --> 00:02:02,245
Meet me at the printers at 6:00.

31
00:02:03,227 --> 00:02:06,348
- Can't you just pick one?
- I'm gonna pretend I didn't hear that.

32
00:02:06,473 --> 00:02:08,861
I'm just saying you have great taste.
I don't...

33
00:02:09,049 --> 00:02:10,296
need to be there.

34
00:02:11,972 --> 00:02:13,173
Kick ass today.

35
00:02:25,363 --> 00:02:26,812
I might be home late tonight.

36
00:02:27,774 --> 00:02:30,000
I'm covering the E.R.
for Sally again.

37
00:02:31,696 --> 00:02:34,653
- I tried to get out of it.
- You don't have to explain.

38
00:02:35,007 --> 00:02:37,782
It's hard 'cause Crosby's out of town,
so there is no one else.

39
00:02:39,121 --> 00:02:40,701
You don't have to explain.

40
00:02:41,378 --> 00:02:42,286
I trust you.

41
00:02:43,335 --> 00:02:44,144
Good.

42
00:02:44,710 --> 00:02:45,952
I trust you, too.

43
00:02:53,642 --> 00:02:56,217
It's like everything I say
comes out wrong.

44
00:02:56,418 --> 00:02:57,418
Everything.

45
00:02:57,934 --> 00:02:59,534
Even when we're good, it's tense.

46
00:02:59,659 --> 00:03:02,514
Things have changed for everybody.
It's a new world.

47
00:03:03,895 --> 00:03:05,351
I miss the old one then.

48
00:03:05,759 --> 00:03:06,759
Really?

49
00:03:07,052 --> 00:03:09,939
When you used to crash on my couch
playing "Madden" till 4:00 am?

50
00:03:10,162 --> 00:03:11,404
Don't you mean futon

51
00:03:11,587 --> 00:03:13,523
and kicking your ass until 4:00 am?

52
00:03:13,648 --> 00:03:15,260
- What?
- What? I said it.

53
00:03:16,195 --> 00:03:18,751
You didn't kick anything.
You were... cheating.

54
00:03:18,876 --> 00:03:20,533
That's what you were doing.

55
00:03:20,702 --> 00:03:21,979
What you call cheating

56
00:03:22,161 --> 00:03:24,613
I call finding a way
to change the game, my friend.

57
00:03:28,643 --> 00:03:30,918
- How's Hawk doing?
- She's out of the woods.

58
00:03:31,247 --> 00:03:33,089
Should be back to work
in a few weeks.

59
00:03:33,214 --> 00:03:35,092
These three had to do
with her shooting?

60
00:03:35,217 --> 00:03:37,942
We followed the hand stamp
from the guy who shot Janis,

61
00:03:38,825 --> 00:03:40,998
led us to the house
where we found these guys.

62
00:03:41,391 --> 00:03:42,555
The Blue Hand stamp?

63
00:03:43,619 --> 00:03:45,976
- I'm sensing a theme.
- You want to share?

64
00:03:46,569 --> 00:03:50,035
The contact ring, residue patterns
and bullet trajectories

65
00:03:50,160 --> 00:03:52,356
are consistent
with self-inflicted gunshot wounds.

66
00:03:52,481 --> 00:03:53,565
Self-inflicted?

67
00:03:54,399 --> 00:03:56,910
You think this is some kind
of suicide pact?

68
00:03:57,241 --> 00:03:58,116
Had to be.

69
00:03:58,241 --> 00:04:00,281
But then who arranged the bodies

70
00:04:00,406 --> 00:04:02,165
and covered them with the sheets?

71
00:04:03,171 --> 00:04:06,370
All had alcohol in their systems.
She had ecstasy and heroin.

72
00:04:06,539 --> 00:04:08,101
Who are these people?

73
00:04:08,623 --> 00:04:11,429
Jason Martinez, 37.
Married, two children.

74
00:04:11,627 --> 00:04:14,067
This is Diana Davis.
Still looking for next of kin,

75
00:04:14,192 --> 00:04:16,434
And Ian Rutherford, 25.

76
00:04:18,317 --> 00:04:21,135
British national reported missing
from a cargo vessel

77
00:04:21,512 --> 00:04:22,684
docked in Long Beach.

78
00:04:26,046 --> 00:04:27,224
Your Rutherford case?

79
00:04:33,647 --> 00:04:34,648
Here we go.

80
00:04:35,615 --> 00:04:37,839
<i>Season 1 Episode 07
The Gift</i>

81
00:04:43,823 --> 00:04:45,432
- Hey, Aaron.
- What's up, Jack?

82
00:04:45,887 --> 00:04:49,216
There's a guy waiting for you inside.
Says he served with Tracy.

83
00:05:11,573 --> 00:05:13,562
- How can I help you?
- You're Aaron Stark?

84
00:05:15,480 --> 00:05:16,927
Corporal Mike Willingham.

85
00:05:17,486 --> 00:05:19,443
I wanted to talk to you
for a while, but...

86
00:05:19,568 --> 00:05:22,153
but I've been mixed up,
trying to get a job, a place to live.

87
00:05:23,424 --> 00:05:24,424
It's tough

88
00:05:24,730 --> 00:05:26,436
re-adjusting to civilian life.

89
00:05:26,561 --> 00:05:29,485
With the way things are now,
You just gotta hope it gets better.

90
00:05:30,041 --> 00:05:32,122
Sorry to bother you at work,

91
00:05:32,290 --> 00:05:35,362
but I promised Tracy
that if anything ever happened to her,

92
00:05:35,615 --> 00:05:36,789
I'd give you this.

93
00:05:44,512 --> 00:05:45,775
<i>How did you find me?</i>

94
00:05:46,851 --> 00:05:48,681
<i>I'll always find you, kiddo.</i>

95
00:05:49,462 --> 00:05:52,296
<i>I think right now,
you need this more than I do.</i>

96
00:06:05,259 --> 00:06:06,877
I hadn't seen this knife

97
00:06:07,169 --> 00:06:09,280
since Tracy deployed four years ago,

98
00:06:10,013 --> 00:06:12,253
but somehow...

99
00:06:13,313 --> 00:06:15,707
Now I understand
how in my flash-forward,

100
00:06:17,481 --> 00:06:20,379
- I was giving it back to her.
- She said it was a good luck charm.

101
00:06:21,088 --> 00:06:22,782
Maybe there's something to that.

102
00:06:25,156 --> 00:06:27,700
For two years,
I've had to listen to people telling me

103
00:06:27,967 --> 00:06:28,846
to move on,

104
00:06:29,655 --> 00:06:32,963
to accept what happened to her.
But I always knew I'd see her again.

105
00:06:33,417 --> 00:06:35,297
Now you showing up here...

106
00:06:40,673 --> 00:06:42,257
It's all happening, isn't it?

107
00:06:44,553 --> 00:06:45,816
It's all happening.

108
00:06:57,654 --> 00:06:59,384
Why do a copy machine salesman,

109
00:06:59,509 --> 00:07:00,753
a librarian

110
00:07:00,921 --> 00:07:03,718
and a Scottish journalist decide
to get together to shoot themselves?

111
00:07:03,843 --> 00:07:05,090
Because print is dead?

112
00:07:07,450 --> 00:07:08,761
Say hello to your vision.

113
00:07:09,266 --> 00:07:10,930
You all know Fiona Banks,

114
00:07:11,055 --> 00:07:13,516
MI6, fresh off the plane
from London.

115
00:07:13,641 --> 00:07:15,020
Nice to meet you again.

116
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:16,977
For the first time.

117
00:07:18,692 --> 00:07:19,833
Nice to meet you.

118
00:07:20,103 --> 00:07:22,587
Suicide seems
a little low-incident for MI6.

119
00:07:22,712 --> 00:07:25,486
Ian Rutherford was reported missing
off a cargo ship two weeks ago.

120
00:07:25,735 --> 00:07:27,300
The British embassy was notified.

121
00:07:27,425 --> 00:07:29,312
I saw the report
and came here because...

122
00:07:29,437 --> 00:07:32,284
'Cause you knew you'd be working
on this case from your flash-forward.

123
00:07:33,703 --> 00:07:35,996
That's all well and good,
but what do we got?

124
00:07:36,164 --> 00:07:38,230
When I found out
all 3 vics committed suicide.

125
00:07:38,355 --> 00:07:40,783
I cross-referenced
their visions on Mosaic.

126
00:07:41,526 --> 00:07:43,126
Turns out they're all ghosts.

127
00:07:44,204 --> 00:07:47,550
So people who didn't see anything,
that's what they call themselves.

128
00:07:47,675 --> 00:07:50,798
So none of them had visions
and now they're all dead.

129
00:07:51,138 --> 00:07:53,445
Am I the only one
who finds that disturbing?

130
00:07:53,639 --> 00:07:54,757
No, you're not.

131
00:07:56,110 --> 00:07:57,935
Here.
Check this out.

132
00:07:58,866 --> 00:08:00,187
It's a ghost web site.

133
00:08:00,797 --> 00:08:04,003
It's where they connect with each other,
find out about upcoming events.

134
00:08:04,721 --> 00:08:06,681
Anchorage, Buenos Aires, Dubai...

135
00:08:06,806 --> 00:08:08,737
It's happening everywhere.

136
00:08:09,162 --> 00:08:11,176
"The Blue Hand.
No limits. No fear.

137
00:08:11,301 --> 00:08:14,698
"A place where ghosts can gather
to embrace the inevitable."

138
00:08:14,823 --> 00:08:16,489
You've got to be kidding me.

139
00:08:16,748 --> 00:08:19,491
- A death club?
- Like a book club, with bullets.

140
00:08:19,666 --> 00:08:22,918
Whatever it is,
the guy who shot Janis is a part of it.

141
00:08:23,086 --> 00:08:26,255
We need to find these people, figure out
who they are and shut them down.

142
00:08:26,423 --> 00:08:29,179
The next meeting in LA is being hosted
by a guy named...

143
00:08:29,606 --> 00:08:31,802
Raynaud.
Dr. Maurice Raynaud.

144
00:08:32,184 --> 00:08:33,429
When is the meeting?

145
00:08:33,888 --> 00:08:35,890
<i>Tonight, go downtown</i>

146
00:08:36,015 --> 00:08:37,891
<i>and check the time.</i>

147
00:08:38,240 --> 00:08:40,268
<i>Tonight, go downtown</i>

148
00:08:40,393 --> 00:08:41,770
<i>and check the time.</i>

149
00:08:52,573 --> 00:08:55,559
Ian Blaine Rutherford.
Born in Edinburgh, 1984.

150
00:08:55,684 --> 00:08:58,234
Father's an aviation mechanic.
Mother...

151
00:08:58,994 --> 00:09:01,765
Works in a factory,
makes cell phone components.

152
00:09:02,776 --> 00:09:04,418
I've already seen that file.

153
00:09:04,586 --> 00:09:05,654
Yes, of course.

154
00:09:07,087 --> 00:09:08,571
Sorry. I just...

155
00:09:08,696 --> 00:09:11,258
I never expected to be working
on this case so soon.

156
00:09:11,426 --> 00:09:13,371
The dominos seem to be

157
00:09:13,877 --> 00:09:15,137
falling into place.

158
00:09:16,860 --> 00:09:17,860
It's funny.

159
00:09:18,649 --> 00:09:21,824
I don't remember anything from
the actual dossier other than his name.

160
00:09:22,812 --> 00:09:24,130
I just remember you.

161
00:09:25,498 --> 00:09:26,440
And the bird.

162
00:09:27,291 --> 00:09:28,753
When it hit the window...

163
00:09:29,402 --> 00:09:31,153
I felt my heart skip a beat.

164
00:09:32,839 --> 00:09:34,381
Then you had the phone call.

165
00:09:35,742 --> 00:09:37,135
<i>Excuse me for a moment.</i>

166
00:09:39,201 --> 00:09:41,496
After you left,
I looked out onto the ledge.

167
00:09:42,826 --> 00:09:43,960
I went over.

168
00:09:51,424 --> 00:09:52,716
I wanted to help it.

169
00:09:54,130 --> 00:09:55,696
If only to end its pain.

170
00:09:56,494 --> 00:09:57,513
But I couldn't.

171
00:09:58,567 --> 00:09:59,890
That was the worst part.

172
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:02,969
There was nothing I could do

173
00:10:03,428 --> 00:10:04,353
to stop it.

174
00:10:15,252 --> 00:10:16,946
What was your phone call about?

175
00:10:17,570 --> 00:10:18,840
It was my attorney.

176
00:10:19,327 --> 00:10:21,986
Why were you speaking to an attorney?
Did something happen?

177
00:10:25,816 --> 00:10:27,042
<i>I killed her.</i>

178
00:10:29,395 --> 00:10:30,830
No, everything was fine.

179
00:10:44,607 --> 00:10:46,372
I'm working downtown tonight.

180
00:10:47,242 --> 00:10:50,089
Thought I might stop by
that bakery on Grand, on the way back,

181
00:10:50,628 --> 00:10:52,652
pick us up some
of those cinnamon rolls.

182
00:10:56,723 --> 00:10:57,723
Or not.

183
00:11:02,877 --> 00:11:05,487
You don't have any idea
why I'm mad, do you?

184
00:11:07,186 --> 00:11:08,336
The printers?

185
00:11:08,960 --> 00:11:10,260
Our invitations?

186
00:11:10,983 --> 00:11:12,454
My God.
I'm so sorry.

187
00:11:14,566 --> 00:11:15,941
Work was so crazy.

188
00:11:16,066 --> 00:11:19,513
We got a lead on the guy who shot Janis
and now we're going to this club.

189
00:11:19,638 --> 00:11:21,879
You're not the only one
who had a crazy day.

190
00:11:22,004 --> 00:11:24,556
I've been cranking out
motions in limine all afternoon

191
00:11:24,681 --> 00:11:25,893
but somehow

192
00:11:26,519 --> 00:11:28,904
- made it to the printers anyway.
- You're right.

193
00:11:29,355 --> 00:11:31,446
I should have been there.
I'm really sorry.

194
00:11:31,571 --> 00:11:33,735
It's not about the invitations.

195
00:11:35,067 --> 00:11:38,008
It's about you and me
and the fact that you've been...

196
00:11:38,578 --> 00:11:40,670
checked out ever since
I got home from Seattle.

197
00:11:40,795 --> 00:11:42,521
I've been slammed
since the blackout.

198
00:11:42,646 --> 00:11:43,717
Since the blackout.

199
00:11:43,842 --> 00:11:45,867
That's been your excuse
for everything.

200
00:11:45,992 --> 00:11:48,844
Yeah, no,
why you are late coming home,

201
00:11:48,969 --> 00:11:50,203
why you don't talking,

202
00:11:50,328 --> 00:11:53,124
why you shut your computer
every time I walk in the room.

203
00:11:53,249 --> 00:11:55,797
- It's like I don't even exist.
- That's unfair.

204
00:11:55,965 --> 00:11:58,838
What's unfair
is being in love with someone

205
00:11:58,963 --> 00:12:01,026
who treats you like a stranger.
That's unfair.

206
00:12:01,151 --> 00:12:03,930
And I don't want you to apologize.

207
00:12:05,115 --> 00:12:08,101
I don't.
I want you to want to be here.

208
00:12:09,176 --> 00:12:10,226
Talk to me.

209
00:12:10,983 --> 00:12:14,149
Just be honest
about whatever's going on.

210
00:12:16,641 --> 00:12:18,453
- You want me to be honest.
- Yes.

211
00:12:21,318 --> 00:12:23,863
The more you jump down my throat,
the less I want to be here.

212
00:12:23,988 --> 00:12:25,350
How's that for honesty?

213
00:12:32,208 --> 00:12:34,274
- Is he qualified?
- No, I think...

214
00:12:34,546 --> 00:12:35,935
Thanks for having me.

215
00:12:36,060 --> 00:12:38,548
Not at all.
We always need volunteers.

216
00:12:39,211 --> 00:12:41,215
There's a lot of menial tasks.

217
00:12:41,340 --> 00:12:43,038
A lot of charts to be filed

218
00:12:43,793 --> 00:12:45,314
and blood to be run to the lab.

219
00:12:45,439 --> 00:12:47,925
- It's not glamorous.
- I'm not looking for glamour.

220
00:12:48,851 --> 00:12:50,729
Aren't you supposed to be
at that conference?

221
00:12:50,854 --> 00:12:53,647
Yes, but lab's lost the coags
on our spider girl,

222
00:12:53,815 --> 00:12:55,691
the O.R. is trying to bump our appy,

223
00:12:55,859 --> 00:12:58,065
and volvulus guy is leaving the AMA

224
00:12:58,236 --> 00:13:00,108
to see his kid
in this ice capades thing.

225
00:13:00,233 --> 00:13:02,557
So redraw the coags, tell the OR no,

226
00:13:02,682 --> 00:13:04,379
and I'll talk to skater dad.

227
00:13:04,504 --> 00:13:06,671
- Bryce, do you know Nicole?
- Yeah.

228
00:13:06,796 --> 00:13:09,630
I think we met
at your christmas party last year. Hi.

229
00:13:09,850 --> 00:13:11,248
Nicole's volunteering here.

230
00:13:11,416 --> 00:13:13,458
He'll show you the lay of the land.

231
00:13:13,908 --> 00:13:15,451
I will catch you later.

232
00:13:17,163 --> 00:13:18,839
- Thanks.
- What's "volvulus"?

233
00:13:19,197 --> 00:13:20,173
Twisted gut.

234
00:13:21,669 --> 00:13:22,769
You pre-med?

235
00:13:23,461 --> 00:13:26,805
No, I'm just volunteering,
helping people, you know.

236
00:13:30,925 --> 00:13:33,353
Ma'am, slow down. I'm sorry.
We don't understand you.

237
00:13:48,542 --> 00:13:49,409
<i>Arigato.</i>

238
00:13:51,033 --> 00:13:53,425
Sweet peas symbolize good-bye
in japanese culture.

239
00:13:53,550 --> 00:13:55,994
It's considered a bad omen
to give it to the sick.

240
00:13:59,940 --> 00:14:01,157
Is that a cardigan?

241
00:14:01,525 --> 00:14:02,360
What?

242
00:14:02,584 --> 00:14:04,210
I was going for Average Joe.

243
00:14:04,652 --> 00:14:07,840
Back off, Dem.
That jacket? Ridiculous.

244
00:14:08,681 --> 00:14:11,398
Says the FBI agent in a police T-shirt.
Good going.

245
00:14:14,312 --> 00:14:15,312
What?

246
00:14:16,027 --> 00:14:18,565
"Go downtown, check the time."

247
00:14:42,231 --> 00:14:44,131
We're here for the meeting.

248
00:14:46,910 --> 00:14:49,443
At Dr. Raynaud's invitation.

249
00:15:38,054 --> 00:15:39,312
